The NBA and Warner Bros. Discovery
----------------------------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/business/media/nbc-prepa=
res-roughly-2-5-billion-a-year-offer-to-steal-nba-rights-away-from-tnt-e6e1=
4eeb ) :

Comcast=E2=80=99s NBCUniversal is prepared to pay an average of about $2.5 =
billion a year to air a package of National Basketball Association games, a=
s rival Warner Bros. Discovery makes last-ditch efforts to keep those right=
s, say people familiar with the situation. Warner=E2=80=99s TNT is one of t=
he league=E2=80=99s oldest television partners and has paid an average fee =
of $1.2 billion under its current deal. Warner was unable to reach a new pa=
ct with the NBA before an exclusive negotiating window expired last week, w=
hich allowed NBC to make a bid.

The package NBCUniversal is bidding on would include playoff and regular se=
ason games that would appear on the NBC network, as well as its Peacock str=
eaming service. NBC has discussed carrying two prime-time games a week, som=
ething Warner can=E2=80=99t offer because it doesn=E2=80=99t own a broadcas=
t network. Sports rights are coveted assets for both traditional media comp=
anies fighting to keep cable subscribers and streamers trying to attract an=
d retain customers. The league=E2=80=99s discussions with partners for the =
new round of media-rights deals=E2=80=94which would kick in after the 2024-=
2025 season and last about a decade=E2=80=94are in the advanced stages.

Disney, the parent of ESPN and ABC, is the other major TV partner and is ex=
pected to pay an average per-year fee of about $2.6 billion to renew its de=
al, the people familiar with the situation said, up from about $1.5 billion=
 a year now. Each TV partner would air fewer games under their new deals th=
an under the current pacts. The league took some games away from its TV par=
tners during this year=E2=80=99s rights negotiations to create a package fo=
r a streaming partner. Amazon=E2=80=99s Prime Video has already reached the=
 outlines of a streaming rights deal with the NBA.

First off, these are just reports: the only thing we know for sure about th=
e NBA media deal is that the exclusive negotiating window for ESPN and Warn=
er Bros. Discovery to renew their deals expired last week. What also seems =
clear is that the NBA is not going to triple its rights fees, which is the =
number the league was floating as recently as last fall ( https://strateche=
