The long run bull case for Netflix isn=E2=80=99t just that they survive mak=
ing their own content, but rather that they move on from disrupting the cab=
le bundle to basically being the cable bundle for everything but sports (an=
d they=E2=80=99re even creeping in that direction when the money and opport=
unity makes sense). To that end, as their streaming competitors start to fa=
lter under huge losses and challenges around customer acquisition and churn=
 mitigation, it is natural to expect that Netflix might start leveraging it=
s position to start buying content from studios desperate to actually make =
money on their shows again. The company is certainly starting to do that he=
re and there, but Sarandos made clear that Netflix isn=E2=80=99t going to b=
reak its budget to seize the opportunity=E2=80=A6

Basically, I get the sense that Netflix is hunkering down a bit for a slowe=
r growth consolidation phase, where it builds up the tech for recommendatio=
ns and ads (which are very much related!) in a way that will allow it to se=
rve even more content to even more people. That=E2=80=99s not necessarily a=
n approach that is going to lead to outsized subscriber growth in the short=
 term, particularly once the password sharing crackdown is over; it is some=
thing that can lead to solid profit and free cash flow numbers as long as t=
hey stay disciplined in their spending, especially if improved recommendati=
ons can drive even deeper engagement with their existing content.

I also think that Netflix can afford to wait: its competitors are seeking t=
o sell the occasional show to get cash to continue funding their streaming =
dreams; why should Netflix go out of its way to help fund those? The compan=
y can be selective with the content it acquires, improve its tech, and bide=
 its time until competing services finally give up on being streamers and a=
ccept their role as studios, on Netflix=E2=80=99s terms, and on a platform =
that is truly ready to be the only TV you need.

The most important paragraph here is that last one: Netflix=E2=80=99s compe=
titors haven=E2=80=99t thrown in the towel yet, which, by extension, means =
the NBA is still valuable, because tentpole sports still make the core busi=
ness models of these bidders work =E2=80=94 and you need a business that wo=
rks if you=E2=80=99re going to continue incinerating cash on streaming. Thi=
s applies to all three of these bidders, but in slightly different ways:

* Disney both wants to maintain the value of ESPN in the cable bundle, whic=
h means having tentpole programming in the spring and summer (i.e. the NBA =
playoffs), even as it readies plans to launch a standalone streaming servic=
e (which itself needs year-round content to prevent churn).
* When it comes to NBC, retransmission fees are still growing substantially=
 (7% year-over-year last quarter), which was third behind Fox (10%) and ABC=
 (8%) but ahead of CBS (2%); it seems reasonable to expect that NBC can dri=
ve those fees higher with the NBA, and the NBA I=E2=80=99m sure likes the i=
dea of being available over-the-air. And, of course, Peacock seems determin=
ed to grow its streaming business on rented rights.

It=E2=80=99s Warner Bros. Discovery that is in the most difficult position:=
 affiliate fees are declining (-5%), without a broadcast network providing =
increased retransmission fees, and the company continues to have a big debt=
 load and a money-losing streaming business (that has numbers that look bet=
ter =E2=80=94 profitable last quarter on an adjusted basis =E2=80=94 when y=
ou include traditional linear HBO subscriptions). Whether the company match=
es NBC=E2=80=99s offer strikes me as a crossroads; the Wall Street Journal =
article notes:

Warner=E2=80=99s TNT has the ability to try to match rival offers, people f=
amiliar with its pact said. For Warner, the loss of the NBA would be a blow=
 to the strength of its TNT cable network at the same time it is being hurt=
 by cord-cutting and a shrinking advertising marketplace.

TNT still has a heavy roster of sports, including the NCAA March Madness co=
llege-basketball tournament, the NHL and Nascar. Without the NBA, though, W=
arner could have a harder time charging distributors as much for carriage o=
f its channels. Warner=E2=80=99s networks currently bring in about $3 a mon=
th per cable customer, according to a person familiar with the matter.

That NCAA deal is an interesting one: CBS and Turner signed an eight-year e=
xtension to their deal with the NCAA back in 2016 ( https://www.sportsmedia=
watch.com/2016/04/cbs-turner-ncaa-march-madness-eight-year-extension-final-=
four-cable-2032/ ) , even though their then-current deal didn=E2=80=99t exp=
ire until this year! To put that in perspective, in between the time when t=
his deal was signed and when it goes into effect (next year) Turner sports =
went from being owned by Time Warner to Time Warner being owned by AT&T to =
Time Warner being spun out to Discovery to form today=E2=80=99s Warner Bros=
. Discovery.

