*I have more conceptual question for Satya. If you think about Copilots and=
 what you=E2=80=99re doing there, you=E2=80=99re kind of impacting a lot of=
 this in businesses and the opportunities seem very broad-based. How do you=
 think this will play out in the industry between you guys offering certain=
 Copilots, versus like the rest of the industry following, and everyone see=
ms to have a Copilot now and seems to be talking about it. How does that im=
pact what do you want to do, your partner strategy going forward?*

*Nadella:* It=E2=80=99s a great question. So the way we see it play out is,=
 if you think about it, the way Office was used broadly for knowledge work =
was in the context of business processes, right? So it=E2=80=99s not like =
=E2=80=93 when people do knowledge work, they=E2=80=99re not doing knowledg=
e work, they=E2=80=99re doing knowledge work in support of making progress =
in the context of sales enablement, customer service, revenue ops, supply c=
hain or what have you, right? So that=E2=80=99s the first thing to note. An=
d they do it inside of e-mail. They do it inside of Teams. They do it insid=
e of Excel, PowerPoint, Word and what have you.

Now we have the ability to essentially bridge the work and the work artifac=
ts inside of these knowledge worker tools with the workflow and the busines=
s process and the business process data. So when we think about our Copilot=
, our Copilot has that ability to integrate, whether it=E2=80=99s with Serv=
iceNow, it has the ability to integrate with SAP with Salesforce, with obvi=
ously Dynamics. That=E2=80=99s what we are seeing.

In fact, you=E2=80=99ll hear us talk a lot about it at our developer confer=
ence, which is the extensibility, and Copilot Studio is really off to the r=
aces in terms of the product that most people are excited because one of th=
e things in the enterprise if you want to ground your Copilot with enterpri=
se data, which is in all of these SaaS applications and Copilot Studio is t=
he tool to use it, to make that happen. And so that=E2=80=99s what we are s=
eeing, which is we are building a Copilot, which also happens to be an orch=
estrator of all in other Copilots, which to us appear as extensions. And ne=
t-net, what happens is some of these knowledge worker tools that people hav=
e used all the time, right?

Because when you think about Teams, when you=E2=80=99re having a meeting, y=
ou=E2=80=99re not doing a random meeting, the meeting is in the context of =
some business process. It could be a supply chain meeting where you=E2=80=
=99re trying to understand which suppliers to bet on or what terms to do. A=
nd so now you can access all that data right in the Team=E2=80=99s context.=
 So that=E2=80=99s I think what=E2=80=99s exciting for us, having built all=
 these horizontal tools, which I would say we=E2=80=99re under under-apprec=
iated for the amount of work, how people use those tools to make progress o=
n business process, but we now get to bridge that between the business appl=
ications and knowledge worker tools, tomorrow horizontally.

There is plenty of appreciation here Satya! This is a point I have made for=
 many years about why Microsoft wins with so many businesses where =E2=80=
=9Cbest-in-breed=E2=80=9D startups hit the wall: no one gets a chat client =
to chat, or a word processor to word process, or whatever it might be; they=
 get these software tools to get a job done, and Microsoft excels by making=
 good enough products work together well enough that you can focus on actua=
lly doing business instead of solving IT problems.

